{"title_page": "William Frankland (allergist)", "text_new": "{{short description|British immunologist}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = William Frankland\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]]\n| image              = File:Dr Bill Frankland.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = William Frankland in 2006\n| birth_name         = Alfred William Frankland\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=no|1912|3|19}}\n| birth_place        = [[Sussex, England]], UK\n| death_date         = 2 April 2020\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| education          = [[Rossall School]], [[Carlisle Grammar School]] and [[St. Bees School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Oxford]]\n| nationality        = British\n| occupation         = Allergist\n| years_active       = 1946\u20132020\n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| module             = {{infobox military person|embed=yes\n|allegiance        = {{flag|Great Britain}}\n|branch            = {{army|United Kingdom}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Alfred William (Bill) Frankland''' [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (19 March 1912 - 2 April 2020) was a British [[allergist]] and [[immunology|immunologist]]<ref name=Lane>{{cite journal|last=Lane|first=Richard|title=Bill Frankland: Active allergist at 101|journal=[[The Lancet]]|volume=382|issue=9894|pages=762|year=2013|pmid=23993179|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(13)61821-8}}</ref> whose achievements included the popularisation of the [[pollen count]] as a piece of weather-related information to the British public, and the prediction of increased levels of [[allergy]] to [[penicillin]]. He continued to work, several years after [[centenarian|turning 100]].<ref name=\"Centenary\">{{cite news|last=Hanlon|first=Michael|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/9154756/Dr-Bill-Frankland-I-got-a-call-to-treat-Saddam-for-an-allergy.html|title=Dr Bill Frankland: 'I got a call to treat Saddam for an allergy'|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=20 March 2012|accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nFrankland was born in [[Battle, East Sussex|Battle, Sussex]], England, to Rev. Henry Frankland, of [[North Yorkshire]] farming stock, at the time of his son's birth, curate of St Mark's, Little Common, near [[Bexhill-on-Sea]], [[East Sussex]], in later years a vicar in [[Cumberland]], and (Alice) Rose, daughter of Henry West, a successful ironmonger of [[Barnsley]].<ref name=Hell>{{cite book|title=From Hell Island To Hay Fever: The Life of Dr Bill Frankland|author=Paul Watkins|publisher=Brown Dog Books|year=2018}}</ref><ref name=Centenary/> He was born an identical twin; his brother (the elder twin by fifteen minutes), Rev. John Ashlin Frankland, who worked in [[Sierra Leone]] in the 1950s,<ref name=Hell/><ref>Crockford's Clerical Directory, vol. 90, 1987/88, Oxford University Press, 1987, p. 194</ref> died in 1995 at age 83. They had an elder brother, Basil, who entered the fur trade in [[Canada]], and an elder sister, Ella, who died young (in 1933).<ref name=Hell/><ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anaphylaxis.org.uk/about-us/honorary-president/a-life-in-allergy|title= A Life in Allergy|author=The Anaphlaxis Campaign|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> Frankland reports that the family doctor was ineffective, and this motivated him to do better himself.<ref name=Lane/> His childhood was spent in the [[Lake District]], and he attended the preparatory school at [[Rossall School]], [[Carlisle Grammar School]], then [[St Bees School]].<ref name=Centenary/><ref name=Hell/> He subsequently read medicine at [[The Queen's College, Oxford]] and [[St Mary's Hospital Medical School]], now part of [[Imperial College London]].<ref name=Centenary/><ref name=Lane/>\n\n==Military service==\n\nFrankland spent the war years 1939\u201345 in the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]]; three and a half of them were spent as a [[prisoner of war|POW]] in [[Singapore]]. He would later recall... \"Medically, as a prisoner of war, we saw conditions which are now unknown\".<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n==Post-war academic career==\n\nIn 1946, Frankland began full-time work in the Allergy Department of [[St Mary's Hospital, London]].<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\" /> He and his colleagues undertook a series of trials on between 25,000 and 30,000 patients,<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/> which proved that [[antihistamine]] tablets neither reduced nor increased the incidence of pollen asthma. Frankland has continued to contribute articles to [[academic journals]] beyond his official retirement and his 100th birthday.<ref name=Lane/>\n\n===Hygiene hypothesis===\n\nFrankland believed that the rise in allergies results from increased cleanliness and the levels of hygiene in modern life; the so-called [[hygiene hypothesis]]. He has said that \"We don't set off our immune system early on, we are too clean. In the former East Germany for instance, with very poor work and housing conditions, people were less allergic\".<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===Pollen count===\n\nFrankland was keen to provide patients he saw in London with information about pollens, such as the levels of pollen on any given day, and the times of year when levels would tend to be at their highest. St. Mary's Hospital employed a botanist to assist with collecting this information, and to complement the work on pollen counts already being measured in [[Cardiff]]. Weekly London pollen counts were sent to members of the British Allergy Society from 1953 and shared publicly, through daily news outlets, from 1963.\n\n===Self-experimentation===\n\nHe was also a supporter of the idea of [[Desensitization (medicine)|desensitisation]], a technique which aims to reduce the level of immune response to allergens by repeated low doses of the substance to which the patient has an allergy. In 1955, Frankland experimented on himself by being bitten each day by the blood-sucking insect [[Rhodnius prolixus]]. He was assisted in this work by the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]], which was able to supply insects which Frankland could be sure he had never previously been exposed to. The bites eventually provoked a severe [[anaphylaxis|anaphylactic reaction]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bsaci.org/LiteratureRetrieve.aspx?ID=134068&A=SearchResult&SearchID=1670263&\n|accessdate=16 April 2015|title= Dr A W (Bill) Frankland|publisher=British Society for Allergy and Clinical Immuniology}}</ref>\n\nThis research contributed to an understanding of how long injections of allergens would need to be given to achieve desensitisation. Results varied by individual, but immunity to pollen was found on average after three years. Immunity to venom-based allergens took longer, and was found on average after five years.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===Collaboration with Alexander Fleming===\n\nDuring the 1950s, Frankland served as a [[Specialist registrar|registrar]] to [[Alexander Fleming]] in the development of penicillin. The two had a daily meeting, but due to Fleming's lack of interest in clinical medicine, Frankland has said that he cannot recall a patient ever being discussed. Later, Frankland wrote a chapter on penicillin for a book edited by Fleming. Although largely content with the initial draft, Fleming is reported to have replaced Frankland's closing comment that \"due to increased use, allergy to penicillin is expected to increase\" with \"due to increased purity [of production], allergy to penicillin is likely to decrease.\"\n\nFrankland has since acknowledged that Fleming may have been \"partly right\" because the quality of penicillin production at the time was poor.\nIn 1954, Frankland published \"Prophylaxis of summer Hay-fever and Asthma\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Frankland|first1=A. W.|last2=Augustin|first2=R.|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(54)91620-7|pmid=13164324|title=Prophylaxis of Summer Hay-Fever and Asthma|journal=The Lancet|volume=263|issue=6821|pages=1055\u20137|year=1954}}</ref> The article reported the results of a trial involving 200 patients with previous histories of grass pollen sensitivity half treated with active vaccines, and half with inactive 'control' vaccines.\n\nThe results suggested that the active vaccines were much more effective in reducing allergy symptoms than the controls. The study was notable for being the first in the field which used randomised, controlled methods and a standardised approach to every patient.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Keirns|first1=Carla C|editor1-last=Kroker|editor1-first=Kenton|editor2-last=Keelan|editor2-first=Jennifer|editor3-last=Muzumdar|editor3-first=Pauline|chapterurl=http://www.stonybrook.edu/bioethics/gvandallergy.pdf|chapter=Germs, vaccines, and the rise of allergy|title=Crafting Immunity: Working Histories of Clinical Immunology|year=2008|publisher=Aldershot|page=93}}</ref> The trial, along with his work on the pollen count, was one of the contributing factors to Frankland being awarded the [[European Academy of Allergy and Clinical Immunology|EAACI]] Noon Award for significant contributions to immunotherapy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eaaci.org/resources/grants-a-awards/awardees/1669-eaaci-noon-award-2011.html|title=Grants and Awards|publisher=EACCI|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Saddam Hussein===\n\nIn 1979 Frankland treated Iraq\u2019s then president [[Saddam Hussein]]. Contacted to visit a VIP in Baghdad having trouble with asthma, Frankland advised Hussein this was not the case and to give up his habit of 40 cigarettes a day. Frankland has said \u201cTo my lasting regret, I told him that was his trouble and that if he carried on, in another two years he wouldn\u2019t be head of state. I heard some time later that he had had a disagreement with his secretary of state for health, so he took him outside and shot him. Maybe I was lucky.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/105-year-old-doctor-william-frankland-pow-camp-second-world-war-saddam-hussein-treat-a7660611.html|title=105-year-old doctor still working after surviving Second World War POW camp and treating Saddam Hussein|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=31 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Horton|first1=Helena|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/31/meet-105-year-old-doctor-still-hard-work/|title=Meet the 105-year-old doctor who is still hard at work|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=31 March 2017}}</ref> Hussein was executed in Baghdad on 30 December 2006 following the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]].\n\n===Retirement===\nFrankland retired from his job at St Mary's Hospital at 65, but was then offered an unpaid consultancy role in the Department of Medicine at [[Guy's Hospital]]. He worked at Guy's on this basis for another twenty years on peanut [[anaphylaxis]] and [[Pediatrics|paediatric]] allergies. After retiring from Guy's he continued to participate in academic life by attending conferences and publishing articles in journals.<ref name=Lane/>\n\nIn February 2012, Frankland appeared as an expert witness in a British court. The accused had claimed that a vehicle crash in which he was involved was caused by his losing control following a [[bee sting]]. Although Frankland agreed with the defence that such a scenario was possible, he gave an opinion that delayed-response reactions to bee stings only occurred after there had been initial symptoms following the sting. In this case there had not been such symptoms, and the accused was found guilty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/worlds-oldest-expert-witness-william-frankland/story-fnb64oi6-1226283231827|title=World's oldest expert witness William Frankland|work=The Australian|date=28 February 2012|accessdate=13 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he appeared in an episode of the [[BBC 2]] TV series ''Britain's Greatest Generation'' and as a guest on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Butcher|first=David|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/dmdnpp/britains-greatest-generation--series-1---3-the-fight-for-freedom|title=Britain's Greatest Generation: Series 1 \u2013 3. The Fight for Freedom|work=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/world/597037/Saddam-Hussein-doctor-order-quit-smoking-cigarettes|first=Camilla|last=Tominey|title='Stub it out': Saddam's doctor ordered him to quit smoking|work=Daily Express|date=9 August 2015|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> In June 2015, at the age of 103, he was awarded an [[MBE]] for services to allergy research.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/the-queens-birthday-honours-2015|title=The Queen's Birthday Honours 2015|publisher=Cabinet Office|date=12 June 2015|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/jun/12/queens-birthday-honours-list-2014-mbe|title=Queen's birthday honours list 2015: MBE|agency=Press Association|date=12 June 2015|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> In July 2015 he was, at age 103, the oldest recipient of the badge of the [[Order of Mercy]].<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 7 November 2015</ref>\n\nFrankland continues to publish; at age 100 he authored \"100 years of allergen immunotherapy\",<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.4024/36FR12A.jbpc.13.02|title=100 years of allergen immunotherapy|journal=J. Biol. Phys. Chem.|volume=13|issue=2|pages=53\u201360|year=2013|last=Frankland|first=W.A.}}</ref> and most recently co-authoring, \"Flight Lieutenant Peach's observations on Burning Feet Syndrome in Far Eastern Prisoners of War 1942\u201345\" in the journal ''[[QJM (journal)|QJM]]'' in 2016 (aged 104).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Roocroft|first1=N.T.|last2=Mayhew|first2=E.|last3=Parkes|first3=M.|last4=Frankland|first4=W.A.|last5=Gill|first5=G.V.|last6=Bouhassira|first6=D.|last7=Rice|first7=A. S. C.|doi=10.1093/qjmed/hcw195|pmid=28069916|title=Flight Lieutenant Peach's observations on Burning Feet Syndrome in Far Eastern Prisoners of War 1942\u201345|journal=QJM|volume=110|issue=3|pages=131\u2013139|year=2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, in an interview for his 108th birthday during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], he recounted some memories of the [[1918 flu pandemic]].<ref name=\"Evans2020\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196273/dr-bill-frankland-grandfather-allergy-celebrates/|title=Dr Bill Frankland, the grandfather of allergy, celebrates his 108th birthday {{!}} Imperial News {{!}} Imperial College London|last=|first=|date=|website=Imperial News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Involvement with professional and charitable associations==\n\n===British Society for Allergy and Clinical Immunology===\nIn 1948, Frankland was instrumental in the creation of the British Association of Allergists. The speakers at the Association's inaugural meeting included Sir [[Henry Hallett Dale|Henry Dale]], [[pharmacologist]] and chairman of the board at the [[Wellcome Trust]], and Dr. John Freeman.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/> In 1962 the Association became the British Allergy Society, and Frankland served as president between 1963 and 1966. The society became the British Society for Allergy and Clinical Immunology (BSACI) in 1973.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===International Association of Aerobiology===\nFrankland is a founder member (in 1970) and president.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===Anaphylaxis Campaign===\nFrankland is president of the [[Anaphylaxis Campaign]], the UK charity for severe allergy issues.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe William Frankland Award for Outstanding Services in the field of Clinical Allergy is awarded each year at the annual meeting of the [[BSACI]].<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/> The allergy clinic at St Mary's Hospital is named after Frankland.<ref>{{cite book|title=Allergy: The History of a Modern Malady|first=Mark|last=Jackson|location=London|publisher=Reaktion Books|year=2006|page=[https://archive.org/details/allergyhistoryof00jack/page/81 81]|isbn=978-1861893338|url=https://archive.org/details/allergyhistoryof00jack|url-access=registration|quote=Allergy unit named after Frankland}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/80032056 Imperial War Museum Interview]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frankland, William}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:British centenarians]]\n[[Category:British immunologists]]\n[[Category:British World War II prisoners of war]]\n[[Category:Burma Railway prisoners]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoners of war held by Japan]]\n[[Category:British Catholics]]\n[[Category:People from Sussex]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British immunologist}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = William Frankland\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]]\n| image              = File:Dr Bill Frankland.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = William Frankland in 2006\n| birth_name         = Alfred William Frankland\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=no|1912|3|19}}\n| birth_place        = [[Sussex, England]], UK\n| death_date         = 2 April 2020\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| education          = [[Rossall School]], [[Carlisle Grammar School]] and [[St. Bees School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Oxford]]\n| nationality        = British\n| occupation         = Allergist\n| years_active       = 1946\u20132020\n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| module             = {{infobox military person|embed=yes\n|allegiance        = {{flag|Great Britain}}\n|branch            = {{army|United Kingdom}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Alfred William (Bill) Frankland''' [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (19 March 1912 - 2 April 2020) was a British [[allergist]] and [[immunology|immunologist]]<ref name=Lane>{{cite journal|last=Lane|first=Richard|title=Bill Frankland: Active allergist at 101|journal=[[The Lancet]]|volume=382|issue=9894|pages=762|year=2013|pmid=23993179|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(13)61821-8}}</ref> whose achievements included the popularisation of the [[pollen count]] as a piece of weather-related information to the British public, and the prediction of increased levels of [[allergy]] to [[penicillin]]. He continued to work, several years after [[centenarian|turning 100]].<ref name=\"Centenary\">{{cite news|last=Hanlon|first=Michael|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/9154756/Dr-Bill-Frankland-I-got-a-call-to-treat-Saddam-for-an-allergy.html|title=Dr Bill Frankland: 'I got a call to treat Saddam for an allergy'|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=20 March 2012|accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nFrankland was born in [[Battle, East Sussex|Battle, Sussex]], England, to Rev. Henry Frankland, of [[North Yorkshire]] farming stock, at the time of his son's birth, curate of St Mark's, Little Common, near [[Bexhill-on-Sea]], [[East Sussex]], in later years a vicar in [[Cumberland]], and (Alice) Rose, daughter of Henry West, a successful ironmonger of [[Barnsley]].<ref name=Hell>{{cite book|title=From Hell Island To Hay Fever: The Life of Dr Bill Frankland|author=Paul Watkins|publisher=Brown Dog Books|year=2018}}</ref><ref name=Centenary/> He was born an identical twin; his brother (the elder twin by fifteen minutes), Rev. John Ashlin Frankland, who worked in [[Sierra Leone]] in the 1950s,<ref name=Hell/><ref>Crockford's Clerical Directory, vol. 90, 1987/88, Oxford University Press, 1987, p. 194</ref> died in 1995 at age 83. They had an elder brother, Basil, who entered the fur trade in [[Canada]], and an elder sister, Ella, who died young (in 1933).<ref name=Hell/><ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anaphylaxis.org.uk/about-us/honorary-president/a-life-in-allergy|title= A Life in Allergy|author=The Anaphlaxis Campaign|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> Frankland reports that the family doctor was ineffective, and this motivated him to do better himself.<ref name=Lane/> His childhood was spent in the [[Lake District]], and he attended the preparatory school at [[Rossall School]], [[Carlisle Grammar School]], then [[St Bees School]].<ref name=Centenary/><ref name=Hell/> He subsequently read medicine at [[The Queen's College, Oxford]] and [[St Mary's Hospital Medical School]], now part of [[Imperial College London]].<ref name=Centenary/><ref name=Lane/>\n\n==Military service==\n\nFrankland spent the war years 1939\u201345 in the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]]; three and a half of them were spent as a [[prisoner of war|POW]] in [[Singapore]]. He would later recall... \"Medically, as a prisoner of war, we saw conditions which are now unknown\".<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n==Post-war academic career==\n\nIn 1946, Frankland began full-time work in the Allergy Department of [[St Mary's Hospital, London]].<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\" /> He and his colleagues undertook a series of trials on between 25,000 and 30,000 patients,<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/> which proved that [[antihistamine]] tablets neither reduced nor increased the incidence of pollen asthma. Frankland has continued to contribute articles to [[academic journals]] beyond his official retirement and his 100th birthday.<ref name=Lane/>\n\n===Hygiene hypothesis===\n\nFrankland believed that the rise in allergies results from increased cleanliness and the levels of hygiene in modern life; the so-called [[hygiene hypothesis]]. He has said that \"We don't set off our immune system early on, we are too clean. In the former East Germany for instance, with very poor work and housing conditions, people were less allergic\".<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===Pollen count===\n\nFrankland was keen to provide patients he saw in London with information about pollens, such as the levels of pollen on any given day, and the times of year when levels would tend to be at their highest. St. Mary's Hospital employed a botanist to assist with collecting this information, and to complement the work on pollen counts already being measured in [[Cardiff]]. Weekly London pollen counts were sent to members of the British Allergy Society from 1953 and shared publicly, through daily news outlets, from 1963.\n\n===Self-experimentation===\n\nHe was also a supporter of the idea of [[Desensitization (medicine)|desensitisation]], a technique which aims to reduce the level of immune response to allergens by repeated low doses of the substance to which the patient has an allergy. In 1955, Frankland experimented on himself by being bitten each day by the blood-sucking insect [[Rhodnius prolixus]]. He was assisted in this work by the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]], which was able to supply insects which Frankland could be sure he had never previously been exposed to. The bites eventually provoked a severe [[anaphylaxis|anaphylactic reaction]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bsaci.org/LiteratureRetrieve.aspx?ID=134068&A=SearchResult&SearchID=1670263&\n|accessdate=16 April 2015|title= Dr A W (Bill) Frankland|publisher=British Society for Allergy and Clinical Immuniology}}</ref>\n\nThis research contributed to an understanding of how long injections of allergens would need to be given to achieve desensitisation. Results varied by individual, but immunity to pollen was found on average after three years. Immunity to venom-based allergens took longer, and was found on average after five years.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===Collaboration with Alexander Fleming===\n\nDuring the 1950s, Frankland served as a [[Specialist registrar|registrar]] to [[Alexander Fleming]] in the development of penicillin. The two had a daily meeting, but due to Fleming's lack of interest in clinical medicine, Frankland has said that he cannot recall a patient ever being discussed. Later, Frankland wrote a chapter on penicillin for a book edited by Fleming. Although largely content with the initial draft, Fleming is reported to have replaced Frankland's closing comment that \"due to increased use, allergy to penicillin is expected to increase\" with \"due to increased purity [of production], allergy to penicillin is likely to decrease.\"\n\nFrankland has since acknowledged that Fleming may have been \"partly right\" because the quality of penicillin production at the time was poor.\nIn 1954, Frankland published \"Prophylaxis of summer Hay-fever and Asthma\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Frankland|first1=A. W.|last2=Augustin|first2=R.|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(54)91620-7|pmid=13164324|title=Prophylaxis of Summer Hay-Fever and Asthma|journal=The Lancet|volume=263|issue=6821|pages=1055\u20137|year=1954}}</ref> The article reported the results of a trial involving 200 patients with previous histories of grass pollen sensitivity half treated with active vaccines, and half with inactive 'control' vaccines.\n\nThe results suggested that the active vaccines were much more effective in reducing allergy symptoms than the controls. The study was notable for being the first in the field which used randomised, controlled methods and a standardised approach to every patient.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Keirns|first1=Carla C|editor1-last=Kroker|editor1-first=Kenton|editor2-last=Keelan|editor2-first=Jennifer|editor3-last=Muzumdar|editor3-first=Pauline|chapterurl=http://www.stonybrook.edu/bioethics/gvandallergy.pdf|chapter=Germs, vaccines, and the rise of allergy|title=Crafting Immunity: Working Histories of Clinical Immunology|year=2008|publisher=Aldershot|page=93}}</ref> The trial, along with his work on the pollen count, was one of the contributing factors to Frankland being awarded the [[European Academy of Allergy and Clinical Immunology|EAACI]] Noon Award for significant contributions to immunotherapy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eaaci.org/resources/grants-a-awards/awardees/1669-eaaci-noon-award-2011.html|title=Grants and Awards|publisher=EACCI|accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Saddam Hussein===\n\nIn 1979 Frankland treated Iraq\u2019s then president [[Saddam Hussein]]. Contacted to visit a VIP in Baghdad having trouble with asthma, Frankland advised Hussein this was not the case and to give up his habit of 40 cigarettes a day. Frankland has said \u201cTo my lasting regret, I told him that was his trouble and that if he carried on, in another two years he wouldn\u2019t be head of state. I heard some time later that he had had a disagreement with his secretary of state for health, so he took him outside and shot him. Maybe I was lucky.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/105-year-old-doctor-william-frankland-pow-camp-second-world-war-saddam-hussein-treat-a7660611.html|title=105-year-old doctor still working after surviving Second World War POW camp and treating Saddam Hussein|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=31 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Horton|first1=Helena|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/31/meet-105-year-old-doctor-still-hard-work/|title=Meet the 105-year-old doctor who is still hard at work|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=31 March 2017}}</ref> Hussein was executed in Baghdad on 30 December 2006 following the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]].\n\n===Retirement===\nFrankland retired from his job at St Mary's Hospital at 65, but was then offered an unpaid consultancy role in the Department of Medicine at [[Guy's Hospital]]. He worked at Guy's on this basis for another twenty years on peanut [[anaphylaxis]] and [[Pediatrics|paediatric]] allergies. After retiring from Guy's he continued to participate in academic life by attending conferences and publishing articles in journals.<ref name=Lane/>\n\nIn February 2012, Frankland appeared as an expert witness in a British court. The accused had claimed that a vehicle crash in which he was involved was caused by his losing control following a [[bee sting]]. Although Frankland agreed with the defence that such a scenario was possible, he gave an opinion that delayed-response reactions to bee stings only occurred after there had been initial symptoms following the sting. In this case there had not been such symptoms, and the accused was found guilty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/worlds-oldest-expert-witness-william-frankland/story-fnb64oi6-1226283231827|title=World's oldest expert witness William Frankland|work=The Australian|date=28 February 2012|accessdate=13 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he appeared in an episode of the [[BBC 2]] TV series ''Britain's Greatest Generation'' and as a guest on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Butcher|first=David|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/dmdnpp/britains-greatest-generation--series-1---3-the-fight-for-freedom|title=Britain's Greatest Generation: Series 1 \u2013 3. The Fight for Freedom|work=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/world/597037/Saddam-Hussein-doctor-order-quit-smoking-cigarettes|first=Camilla|last=Tominey|title='Stub it out': Saddam's doctor ordered him to quit smoking|work=Daily Express|date=9 August 2015|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> In June 2015, at the age of 103, he was awarded an [[MBE]] for services to allergy research.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/the-queens-birthday-honours-2015|title=The Queen's Birthday Honours 2015|publisher=Cabinet Office|date=12 June 2015|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/jun/12/queens-birthday-honours-list-2014-mbe|title=Queen's birthday honours list 2015: MBE|agency=Press Association|date=12 June 2015|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> In July 2015 he was, at age 103, the oldest recipient of the badge of the [[Order of Mercy]].<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 7 November 2015</ref>\n\nFrankland continues to publish; at age 100 he authored \"100 years of allergen immunotherapy\",<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.4024/36FR12A.jbpc.13.02|title=100 years of allergen immunotherapy|journal=J. Biol. Phys. Chem.|volume=13|issue=2|pages=53\u201360|year=2013|last=Frankland|first=W.A.}}</ref> and most recently co-authoring, \"Flight Lieutenant Peach's observations on Burning Feet Syndrome in Far Eastern Prisoners of War 1942\u201345\" in the journal ''[[QJM (journal)|QJM]]'' in 2016 (aged 104).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Roocroft|first1=N.T.|last2=Mayhew|first2=E.|last3=Parkes|first3=M.|last4=Frankland|first4=W.A.|last5=Gill|first5=G.V.|last6=Bouhassira|first6=D.|last7=Rice|first7=A. S. C.|doi=10.1093/qjmed/hcw195|pmid=28069916|title=Flight Lieutenant Peach's observations on Burning Feet Syndrome in Far Eastern Prisoners of War 1942\u201345|journal=QJM|volume=110|issue=3|pages=131\u2013139|year=2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, in an interview for his 108th birthday during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], he recounted some memories of the [[1918 flu pandemic]].<ref name=\"Evans2020\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196273/dr-bill-frankland-grandfather-allergy-celebrates/|title=Dr Bill Frankland, the grandfather of allergy, celebrates his 108th birthday {{!}} Imperial News {{!}} Imperial College London|last=|first=|date=|website=Imperial News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Involvement with professional and charitable associations==\n\n===British Society for Allergy and Clinical Immunology===\nIn 1948, Frankland was instrumental in the creation of the British Association of Allergists. The speakers at the Association's inaugural meeting included Sir [[Henry Hallett Dale|Henry Dale]], [[pharmacologist]] and chairman of the board at the [[Wellcome Trust]], and Dr. John Freeman.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/> In 1962 the Association became the British Allergy Society, and Frankland served as president between 1963 and 1966. The society became the British Society for Allergy and Clinical Immunology (BSACI) in 1973.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===International Association of Aerobiology===\nFrankland is a founder member (in 1970) and president.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n===Anaphylaxis Campaign===\nFrankland is president of the [[Anaphylaxis Campaign]], the UK charity for severe allergy issues.<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe William Frankland Award for Outstanding Services in the field of Clinical Allergy is awarded each year at the annual meeting of the [[BSACI]].<ref name=\"anaphlaxis campaign\"/> The allergy clinic at St Mary's Hospital is named after Frankland.<ref>{{cite book|title=Allergy: The History of a Modern Malady|first=Mark|last=Jackson|location=London|publisher=Reaktion Books|year=2006|page=[https://archive.org/details/allergyhistoryof00jack/page/81 81]|isbn=978-1861893338|url=https://archive.org/details/allergyhistoryof00jack|url-access=registration|quote=Allergy unit named after Frankland}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/80032056 Imperial War Museum Interview]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frankland, William}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:British centenarians]]\n[[Category:British immunologists]]\n[[Category:British World War II prisoners of war]]\n[[Category:Burma Railway prisoners]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoners of war held by Japan]]\n[[Category:British Catholics]]\n[[Category:People from Sussex]]\n", "name_user": "JulesN", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Frankland_(allergist)"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of the viral pandemic in Tamil Nadu, India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current event|2=current disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu\n| image           = Corona Lockdown Tirupur, Tamil Nadu (2).jpg\n| width           = \n| caption         = Empty store shelves in [[Tiruppur]] due to panic buying prior to lockdown\n| map1            = TN COVID-19 cases in districts.svg\n| legend1         = Map of districts with confirmed cases (as of 31 March)\n{{legend|#d45500ff|30+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ff9955ff|10\u201329 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffe6d5ff|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]\n| first_case      = [[Chennai]]\n| arrival_date    = 7 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=07|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 234<ref name=\"TNHFW\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/index.html|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Home|website=stopcorona.tn.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n| active_cases    = 227<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 6<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| deaths          = 1<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| territories     = [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu#District-wise cases|24 districts]] including [[Chennai district|Chennai]], [[Coimbatore district|Coimbatore]], [[Erode district|Erode]], [[Madurai district|Madurai]], [[Namakkal district|Namakkal]], [[Theni district|Theni]] and [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli]]\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{url|https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/}}\n| youtube         = \n}}\nThe first case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] in the Indian state of [[Tamil Nadu]] was confirmed on 7 March 2020. The state has confirmed a total of 234 cases, including 1 death and 6 recoveries, as of 1 April 2020.<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n\n190 (81%) of all reported cases were from one cluster linked to an Islamic religious congregation event that took place in [[Delhi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-covid-19-count-jumps-by-110-in-1-day/articleshow/74940428.cms|title=Coronavirus in Tamil Nadu: Tamil Nadu Covid-19 count jumps by 110 in 1 day {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Narayan|first=Pushpa|last2=Menon|first2=Jaya|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=N|first3=Durgesh|last4=Apr 2|first4=an Jha {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated:|last5=2020|last6=Ist|first6=10:28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gulte.com/news/83733/More-Than-330-Cases-Linked-to-Delhi-Mosque|title=More Than 330 Cases Linked to Delhi Mosque|last=13|date=2020-04-02|website=Gulte|language=english|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The state government has created containment zones in 12 affected districts to survey its residents for checking community spread and to prevent more infections.<ref name=\"containmentNews18\" /><ref name=\"containmentDH\" />\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== March ===\nThe first case of coronavirus was confirmed on 7 March in a resident from [[Kanchipuram]] in [[Chennai]]. He had returned from [[Oman]] and started developing symptoms including fever and cough.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-first-case-of-coronavirus-patient-quarantined-in-government-hospital-in-chennai/articleshow/74529929.cms?from=mdr|title=Tamil Nadu reports first case of Coronavirus; patient quarantined in Chennai Government Hospital|date=2020-03-09|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> He was isolated in [[Government General Hospital, Chennai|Rajiv Gandhi Government General Hospital]]. Later, on 10 March, he recovered and tested negative.<ref name=\"TNrecovered\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-no-fresh-covid-19-cases-in-tamil-nadu-812479.html?utm_campaign=fullarticle&utm_medium=referral&utm_source=inshorts|title=Coronavirus: No fresh COVID-19 cases in Tamil Nadu|date=10 March 2020|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter more than a week without new cases, on 18 March, the second person who had travelled by train from Delhi to Chennai confirmed positive. He did not have any history of foreign travel and was described as a domestic case by the state health minister [[C. Vijayabaskar]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamil Nadu's 2nd Coronavirus patient raises community transmission fears|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|newspaper=Economic Times|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, a 21-year-old student who returned from [[Ireland]] tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|title=Coronavirus LIVE: India's death toll rises to four|website=Business Standard|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, a further three were confirmed positive - A Chennai man who had travelled from [[New Zealand]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|title=Three more COVID-19 cases in State, one with no travel history|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-30|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> and two [[Thailand]] nationals in [[Erode]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-17-fresh-coronavirus-cases-tally-now-67-819262.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 17 fresh coronavirus cases; tally now 67|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> They were admitted to IRT Hospital in Perundurai in Erode. More than 300 people who had come in contact with the three patients were quarantined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-7th-positive-coronavirus-case-816543.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 7th positive coronavirus case|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the first virus-related death in the state was reported after a 54-year-old man in [[Madurai]] died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|title=\u0bae\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0ba9\u0bbe \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bbf : 54 \u0bb5\u0baf\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0baa\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bb0\u0ba3\u0bae\u0bcd {{!}} Patrikai - Tamil Daily - latest online local breaking news & reviews - Tamilnadu, India & World - politics, cinema, cricket, video & cartoon|date=2020-03-25|website=Tamil News patrikai {{!}} Tamil news online {{!}} latest tamil news|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Five others were infected - four Indonesians and their travel guide from Chennai.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-tally-goes-up-to-23/articleshow/74810591.cms|title=Tamil Nadu reports five new coronavirus cases; tally goes up to 23|author=|newspaper=Economic Times|date = 26 March 2020}}</ref> The five were in quarantine since 22 March in Salem Medical College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-reports-5-new-cases-covid-19-includes-4-indonesian-travellers-and-1-chennai-man-121103|title=TN reports 5 new cases of COVID-19, includes 4 Indonesian travellers and 1 Chennai man|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, a 21-year-old youth who had just returned from a trip to [[Dublin]], Ireland was discharged from the hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/covid-19-positive-tamil-nadu-man-with-travel-history-to-ireland-recovers-120032800122_1.html|title=Covid-19 positive Tamil Nadu man with travel history to Ireland recovers|author=|date=28 March 2020|newspaper=Business Standard India|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Two new cases - one each in [[Kumbakonam]] and [[Katpadi]] were reported. With this, the total number of confirmed cases had reached 40 in the state.<ref name=\"28Bulletin\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the state reported eight more cases (four each from Coimbatore and Erode), all of which were linked to the two [[Thailand|Thai]] nationals and their group who had tested positive. The eight included a 10-month-old baby.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|title=10-month-old baby and 7 more test positive for COVID-19 in Tamil Nadu; state's tally rises to 50|date=29 March 2020|work=Deccan Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The total number of confirmed cases reached 50.<ref name=\"29Bulletin\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=29 March 2020|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070556/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, 17 new cases were reported, highest till date in the state<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> - 10 male patients from [[Erode]], all of whom have travelled to Delhi were in contact with the Thailand tourists, 5 in Chennai and 1 each in [[Karur]] and [[Madurai]].<ref name=\"30MarchBulletinOld\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_30_03_20_COVID_19_1_11_AM.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_30_03_20_COVID_19_1_11_AM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, 57 new cases were reported, all with a history of travel predominately to [[Delhi]], bringing the total to 124.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-reports-57-new-covid-19-cases-in-one-day-79-attended-tablighi-jamaat-state-tally-at-124-1661904-2020-03-31|title=Tamil Nadu reports 57 new Covid-19 cases in one day, 79% attended Tablighi Jamaat. State tally at 124|date=|work=India Today|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was the highest single day rise till date. 50 of these cases were from [[Namakkal district|Namakkal]] (18), [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli]] (22), [[Kanyakumari district|Kanyakumari]] (4) [[Viluppuram|Villupuram]] (3), [[Madurai district|Madurai]] (2) and [[Thoothukudi district|Thoothukudi]] (1), all had travel history to Delhi.<ref name=\"31MarBulletin2\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070737/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Officials had discovered that at least 80 out of 124 confirmed cases (79 per cent) in Tamil Nadu were from one cluster as they are direct or indirect contact of the two Thai nationals who had tested positive for on 21 March.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /><ref name=\"Hindu-31March\" /> The Thai nationals, identified as patients 5 and 6 were part of a large group from countries including [[Thailand]], [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]], etc. who had visited the state for an annual pilgrimage.<ref name=\"Hindu-31March\">{{Cite news|last=M|first=Serena Josephine|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|title=25 of 67 patients directly or indirectly linked to Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> This group had also attended a 3-day religious congregation event known as ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in [[New Delhi]] in early March.<ref name=\"March31-DH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-25-out-of-67-in-tamil-nadu-have-contact-or-travel-history-with-thai-nationals-819372.html|title=Coronavirus: 25 out of 67 in Tamil Nadu have contact or travel history with Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> It was estimated that more than 1,500 people from the state had participated in this event.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|title=Coimbatore, Erode Stare at Crisis as Tamil Nadu Govt Races to Trace Scores Back from Nizamuddin Event|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Officials also confirmed that the 54-year-old patient who had died the previous week had also participated in the gathering.  Of 1,500 people who were in the gathering, 1,130 had returned to the state. The government had identified and isolated 515 of the 1,130 people.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /> It faced difficulty while trying to map the rest. It had urged people who attended the gathering to step forward and get tested.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Coronavirus update: Tamil Nadu reports 50 more Covid-19 cases {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mar 31|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated:|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Ist|first3=23:31}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\nOn 1 April, the state reported 110 new cases, all attended the Delhi Nizamuddin event. The total became 234.<ref name=\"April1-IT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-new-coronavirus-cases-linked-nizamuddin-event-tabligh-1662243-2020-04-01|title=Tamil Nadu reports 110 new coronavirus cases, all linked to Nizamuddin event|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/110-more-cases-tamil-nadu-wednesday-all-attended-delhi-jamaat-conference-121630|title=110 more cases in Tamil Nadu on Wednesday, all attended Delhi Jamaat conference|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Health Secretary Beela Rajesh said that 1103  out of 1500 attendees of the event had been traced and isolated. 658 of their samples had been tested of which,190 tested positive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-tamil-nadu-witnesses-steep-rise-in-cases/articleshow/74935016.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu witnesses steep rise in cases|date=2020-04-01|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Some of the participants approached officials themselves after government's request.<ref name=\":2\" /> Family members and close contacts were either taken to quarantine facilities or home quarantined.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/special-containment-plan-for-tj-group/articleshow/74939483.cms|title=Tamil Nadu: Special containment plan for Tablighi Jamaat group {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Apr 2|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated:|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=Ist|first3=08:57}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe data below are based on Health and Family Welfare Department of Tamil Nadu daily reports.\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases chart}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases}}\n\n== Testing ==\nAs of 31 March, the state had 17 laboratories (11 government and 6 private) to handle testing for the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_01.04.2020_6_Pages_English_318_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_01.04.2020_6_Pages_English_318_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/List_of_Private_Laboratories_to_test_COVID_19_30_03_2020_3_Pages_English_604_KB.pdf|title=List_of_Private_Laboratories_to_test_COVID_19_30_03_2020_3_Pages_English_604_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070313/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/List_of_Private_Laboratories_to_test_COVID_19_30_03_2020_3_Pages_English_604_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Goverment_COVID_19_Testing_Lab_ICMR_Support_29032020_5_Pages_English_589_KB.pdf|title=Goverment_COVID_19_Testing_Lab_ICMR_Support_29032020_5_Pages_English_589_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070405/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Goverment_COVID_19_Testing_Lab_ICMR_Support_29032020_5_Pages_English_589_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Initially, it had four government labs.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/pulse/956278/why-kerala-has-done-more-coronavirus-tests-than-tamil-nadu-and-why-this-must-change|title=Why Kerala has done more coronavirus tests than Tamil Nadu \u2013 and why this must change|last=Yamunan|first=Sruthisagar|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The government started screening passengers arriving at the airports in January. It had screened 2,10,538 passengers as of 1 April.\n\nDuring the first half of March, the state faced criticism for low number of tests. By 16 March, it had only tested 90 samples while neighboring Kerala and Karnataka had tested more than 1500 and 750 samples.<ref name=\"Testing-TOI\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/in-tamil-nadu-patients-doctors-call-for-increased-tests-on-coronavirus/articleshow/74647117.cms|title=Coronavirus Tamil Nadu Updates: In Tamil Nadu, patients &amp; doctors call for increased tests on coronavirus {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|date=16 March 2020|agency=TNN |website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The director of Public Health defended the state's low number of tests saying that Kerala saw more travel from coronavirus-affected countries which is why it had detected more cases.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\"/> The Public Health department has also said that the state follows test protocols established by the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare|Union Health Ministry]].<ref name=\"scroll-tests\"/><ref name=\"Testing-TOI\" />\n\nIn order to test community transmission, as of 16 March, the state had tested 22 random samples of people with influenza and severe acute respiratory infection for coronavirus as per [[Indian Council of Medical Research|ICMR]] guidelines. All tested negative.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\"/>\n\nBy 31 March, as part of the door-to-door surveillance, the government had surveyed 3,96,147 people in 1,08,677 houses in the containment and buffer zones of 12 affected districts for fever and other symptoms. It was carried out by over 2,000 personnel.<ref name=\"containmentDH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-coronavirus-cases-rises-to-74-nizamuddin-link-to-a-chunk-of-it-surfaces-819633.html|title=Tamil Nadu coronavirus cases rises to 74, Nizamuddin link to a chunk of it surfaces|date=2020-03-31|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\"CM-News18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/politics/over-2-lakh-passengers-screened-43000-in-home-quarantine-tamil-nadu-cm-assures-state-ready-to-battle-covid-19-2559869.html|title='Over 2 Lakh Passengers Screened, 43,000 in Home Quarantine': Tamil Nadu CM Assures State Ready to Battle Covid-19|date=2020-04-01|website=News18|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the Delhi Nizamuddin event, authorities said that families of 1103 identified participants will be tested whether or not they show symptoms.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAs of 1 April 2726 samples have been tested of which, 234 were positive.<ref name=\"TNHFW\" />\n\n== Containment measures ==\nStickers announcing that \"COVID-19/Do not Visit/Home under quarantine,\" were pasted on the doors of houses of foreign returnees to warn the public. Authorities had also marked their arms with home quarantine stamps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/24/tamil-nadu-goes-under-lockdown-home-quarantine-stickers-pasted-on-doors-of-foreign-returnees-2121106.html|title=Tamil Nadu goes under lockdown; home quarantine stickers pasted on doors of foreign returnees|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Government launched a mobile application to allow people under home quarantine to interact healthcare professionals for getting medical advice and counselling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-launches-app-to-provide-advice-to-those-under-home-quarantine-816562.html|title=Coronavirus: Tamil Nadu launches app to provide advice to those under home quarantine|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, government announced plans for creating containment zones to stop the community spread.<ref name=\"containmentNews18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|title=Tamil Nadu Prepares for Stage Two of Coronavirus Outbreak With More Home Quarantines, Surveillance|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> On 31 March, the government had created containment zones of 5&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> radius around the residences of infected across 12 districts. The containment zone is ringed by an additional 2&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> buffer zone.<ref name=\"containmentDH\" /><ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /> Active door-to-door surveillance inside these zones along with passive surveillance outside of it to trace the contacts of the infected has been initiated. People found infected are quarantined.<ref name=\"CM-News18\" />\n\nAs of 31 March, '''74,533''' passengers who had returned from affected countries are being monitored under 28 day home quarantine. 3470 have completed this quarantine. '''79''' are currently in institutional quarantine facilities across the state.<ref name=\"Daily30Mar\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|title=Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070449/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Governmental response ==\nThe [[Government of Tamil Nadu|state government]] was among the first to launch measures against COVID-19.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /> On 30 January, it had put 78 people who arrived from China under quarantine.<ref name=\"TNborder\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/coronavirus-outbreak-tamil-nadu-closes-borders-constitutes-task-force-120032201274_1.html|title=Coronavirus outbreak: Tamil Nadu closes borders, constitutes task force|work=Business Standard India|access-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The state government had announced a {{INRConvert|3280|c|year=2020}} relief package on 24 March. It included financial support of {{INRConvert|1000|year=2020}} to all ration card holders, free rice and other essential commodities in the wake of [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]]. It also provided registered [[Hawker (trade)|street vendors]], autorickshaw drivers, migrant labourers and construction workers in the state with similar provisions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/tn-announces-3280-crore-relief-package/article31156022.ece|title=TN announces \u20b93,280-crore relief package|last=Bureau|first=Our|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> It had also announced extension periods of three months to make loan and tax payments for all citizens, and one month to pay house rent for workers including migrants across the state.<ref name=\"RentsTNM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-govt-announces-one-month-rent-freeze-action-can-be-taken-if-house-owners-disobey-121552|title=TN govt announces one month rent freeze for workers, including migrants|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Loans-BS\">{{Cite news|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/covid-19-tamil-nadu-gives-3-month-extension-for-payment-of-taxes-loans-120033101318_1.html|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu gives 3-month extension for payment of taxes, loans|date=31 March 2020|work=Business Standard India|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEarlier, it had allocated sum of {{INRConvert|60|c}} from disaster relief fund to deal with the crisis. It had also taken steps to provide medicines for the next two months to patients with hypertension, diabetes mellitus, HIV and TB while also monitoring pregnant women who are due within that time.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Palaniswami|first=Edappadi K.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/an-eye-each-on-containment-and-welfare/article31221845.ece|title=Tamil Nadu CM writes on how the State is stopping the pandemic in its tracks|date=2020-04-01|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/pregnant-women-to-be-monitored/article31167753.ece|title=Pregnant women to be monitored|date=2020-03-25|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-02|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nNewly built [[Tamil Nadu Government Multi Super Speciality Hospital|Omandurar Government Multispeciality Hospital]] in Chennai was converted with 500 beds to exclusively treat COVID-19 patients.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kannan|first=Ramya|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu-announces-dedicated-hospital-for-covid-19-patients/article31146741.ece|title=Tamil Nadu announces dedicated hospital for COVID-19 patients|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 27 March, the government issued appointment order to recruit 530 doctors, 1,000 nurses and 1,508 lab technicians with immediate effect due to the situation. Orders for 200 new ambulances in the state have also been placed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/india/tamil-nadu-recruits-530-doctors-1508-lab-technicians-1000-nurses-to-contain-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak-cm-k-palaniswami-2272083.html|title=Tamil Nadu recruits 530 doctors, 1508 lab technicians, 1000 nurses to contain coronavirus COVID-19 outbreak: CM K Palaniswami|date=2020-03-27|website=Zee News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"CM-News18\" />\n\nOn 31 March, it announced that house rent cannot be taken from workers, including migrant workers, for a period of one month.<ref name=\"RentsTNM\" /> It also extended the time to make payments including loans and taxes by three months.<ref name=\"Loans-BS\" />\n\nThe government has established helplines for public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/whomtocontact.html|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Contact Information|website=stopcorona.tn.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> It also released an app for officials to monitor people under home quarantine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tn-tracks-movements-of-home-quarantine-people-through-a-mobile-app-817853.html|title=Coronavirus: TN tracks movements of home quarantine people through a mobile app|date=2020-03-26|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Suspensions and closedowns ===\nOn 15 March, Chief minister [[Edappadi K. Palaniswami|Edappadi K Palaniswami]] ordered closure of primary schools throughout the state while shutting theatres, commercial complexes and malls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-govt-to-release-rs-60-crore-disaster-relief-funds-to-tackle-coronavirus-shuts-primary-schools-1655752-2020-03-15|title=Tamil Nadu govt to release Rs 60 crore disaster relief fund to tackle coronavirus, shuts primary schools|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> He had also ordered to close state borders with [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]] and [[Andhra Pradesh]] on March 20 until March 31 and constituted a task force to closely monitor the preventive measures against the viral outbreak.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/tn-closes-border-roads-movement-of-essentials-allowed/1774787|title=TN closes border roads, movement of essentials allowed|last=|first=|date=|website=Outlook India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, the Class 10 SSLC board exams were postponed to beyond April 14, which were due to begin from March 27.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/covid-19-tamil-nadus-class-10-board-exams-postponed/article31127217.ece|title=COVID-19: Tamil Nadu's Class 10 board exams postponed|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> Students of class 1\u20139 in the state will be promoted automatically considering the closure of schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/class-1-9-students-will-be-promoted-in-tamil-nadu-due-to-closure-of-schools-cm-11585134717305.html|title=Class 1-9 students will be promoted in Tamil Nadu due to closure of schools: CM|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the state government extended '[[Janata Curfew|''Janata curfew'']]' to Monday morning 5 am.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-govt-extends-janata-curfew-till-monday-morning/articleshow/74758800.cms|title=Tamil Nadu govt extends 'Janata curfew' till Monday morning|date=2020-03-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The next day, it announced that prohibitory orders under [[Unlawful assembly|Section 144]] will start from 24 March 6 pm until March 31 which prohibits gatherings of more than 5 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-imposes-section-144-week-no-gatherings-more-5-people-120912|title=TN imposes Section 144 for a week, no gatherings of more than 5 people|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=www.thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] announced a [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|nationwide lockdown]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html|title=India places millions under lockdown to fight coronavirus|author1=Helen Regan |author2=Esha Mitra |author3=Swati Gupta|date=|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the nationwide lockdown, Chennai suspended delivery of cooked food from services like [[Swiggy]] and [[Zomato]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shrivastava|first=Aditi|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/chennai-bans-delivery-of-cooked-food/articleshow/74837380.cms?from=mdr|title=Chennai bans delivery of cooked food|date=2020-03-27|work=The Economic Times|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://entrackr.com/2020/03/swiggy-and-zomato-not-allowed-to-deliver-in-tamil-nadu/|title=Swiggy and Zomato not allowed to deliver in Tamil Nadu|last=Upadhyay|first=Harsh|date=26 March 2020|website=Entrackr|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The services were allowed by the government after imposing some regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-tamil-nadu-allows-swiggy-zomato-other-apps-to-home-deliver-cooked-food/articleshow/74852688.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu allows Swiggy, Zomato, other apps to home deliver cooked food {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Sundaram|first=Ram|date=27 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\u200e{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Tamil Nadu}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India by state or union territory|Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:2020s in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Health in Tamil Nadu]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of the viral pandemic in Tamil Nadu, India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current event|2=current disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu\n| image           = Corona Lockdown Tirupur, Tamil Nadu (2).jpg\n| width           = \n| caption         = Empty store shelves in [[Tiruppur]] due to panic buying prior to lockdown\n| map1            = TN COVID-19 cases in districts.svg\n| legend1         = Map of districts with confirmed cases (as of 31 March)\n{{legend|#d45500ff|30+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ff9955ff|10\u201329 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffe6d5ff|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]\n| first_case      = [[Chennai]]\n| arrival_date    = 7 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=07|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 234<ref name=\"TNHFW\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/index.html|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Home|website=stopcorona.tn.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n| active_cases    = 227<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 6<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| deaths          = 1<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| territories     = [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu#District-wise cases|24 districts]] including [[Chennai district|Chennai]], [[Coimbatore district|Coimbatore]], [[Erode district|Erode]], [[Madurai district|Madurai]], [[Namakkal district|Namakkal]], [[Theni district|Theni]] and [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli]]\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{url|https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/}}\n| youtube         = \n}}\nThe first case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] in the Indian state of [[Tamil Nadu]] was confirmed on 7 March 2020. The state has confirmed a total of 234 cases, including 1 death and 6 recoveries, as of 1 April 2020.<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n\n190 (81%) of all reported cases were from one cluster linked to an Islamic religious congregation event that took place in [[Delhi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-covid-19-count-jumps-by-110-in-1-day/articleshow/74940428.cms|title=Coronavirus in Tamil Nadu: Tamil Nadu Covid-19 count jumps by 110 in 1 day {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Narayan|first=Pushpa|last2=Menon|first2=Jaya|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=N|first3=Durgesh|last4=Apr 2|first4=an Jha {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated:|last5=2020|last6=Ist|first6=10:28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gulte.com/news/83733/More-Than-330-Cases-Linked-to-Delhi-Mosque|title=More Than 330 Cases Linked to Delhi Mosque|last=13|date=2020-04-02|website=Gulte|language=english|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The state government has created containment zones in 12 affected districts to survey its residents for checking community spread and to prevent more infections.<ref name=\"containmentNews18\" /><ref name=\"containmentDH\" />\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== March ===\nThe first case of coronavirus was confirmed on 7 March in a resident from [[Kanchipuram]] in [[Chennai]]. He had returned from [[Oman]] and started developing symptoms including fever and cough.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-first-case-of-coronavirus-patient-quarantined-in-government-hospital-in-chennai/articleshow/74529929.cms?from=mdr|title=Tamil Nadu reports first case of Coronavirus; patient quarantined in Chennai Government Hospital|date=2020-03-09|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> He was isolated in [[Government General Hospital, Chennai|Rajiv Gandhi Government General Hospital]]. Later, on 10 March, he recovered and tested negative.<ref name=\"TNrecovered\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-no-fresh-covid-19-cases-in-tamil-nadu-812479.html?utm_campaign=fullarticle&utm_medium=referral&utm_source=inshorts|title=Coronavirus: No fresh COVID-19 cases in Tamil Nadu|date=10 March 2020|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter more than a week without new cases, on 18 March, the second person who had travelled by train from Delhi to Chennai confirmed positive. He did not have any history of foreign travel and was described as a domestic case by the state health minister [[C. Vijayabaskar]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamil Nadu's 2nd Coronavirus patient raises community transmission fears|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|newspaper=Economic Times|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, a 21-year-old student who returned from [[Ireland]] tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|title=Coronavirus LIVE: India's death toll rises to four|website=Business Standard|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, a further three were confirmed positive - A Chennai man who had travelled from [[New Zealand]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|title=Three more COVID-19 cases in State, one with no travel history|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-30|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> and two [[Thailand]] nationals in [[Erode]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-17-fresh-coronavirus-cases-tally-now-67-819262.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 17 fresh coronavirus cases; tally now 67|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> They were admitted to IRT Hospital in Perundurai in Erode. More than 300 people who had come in contact with the three patients were quarantined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-7th-positive-coronavirus-case-816543.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 7th positive coronavirus case|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the first virus-related death in the state was reported after a 54-year-old man in [[Madurai]] died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|title=\u0bae\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0ba9\u0bbe \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bbf : 54 \u0bb5\u0baf\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0baa\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bb0\u0ba3\u0bae\u0bcd {{!}} Patrikai - Tamil Daily - latest online local breaking news & reviews - Tamilnadu, India & World - politics, cinema, cricket, video & cartoon|date=2020-03-25|website=Tamil News patrikai {{!}} Tamil news online {{!}} latest tamil news|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Five others were infected - four Indonesians and their travel guide from Chennai.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-tally-goes-up-to-23/articleshow/74810591.cms|title=Tamil Nadu reports five new coronavirus cases; tally goes up to 23|author=|newspaper=Economic Times|date = 26 March 2020}}</ref> The five were in quarantine since 22 March in Salem Medical College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-reports-5-new-cases-covid-19-includes-4-indonesian-travellers-and-1-chennai-man-121103|title=TN reports 5 new cases of COVID-19, includes 4 Indonesian travellers and 1 Chennai man|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, a 21-year-old youth who had just returned from a trip to [[Dublin]], Ireland was discharged from the hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/covid-19-positive-tamil-nadu-man-with-travel-history-to-ireland-recovers-120032800122_1.html|title=Covid-19 positive Tamil Nadu man with travel history to Ireland recovers|author=|date=28 March 2020|newspaper=Business Standard India|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Two new cases - one each in [[Kumbakonam]] and [[Katpadi]] were reported. With this, the total number of confirmed cases had reached 40 in the state.<ref name=\"28Bulletin\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the state reported eight more cases (four each from Coimbatore and Erode), all of which were linked to the two [[Thailand|Thai]] nationals and their group who had tested positive. The eight included a 10-month-old baby.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|title=10-month-old baby and 7 more test positive for COVID-19 in Tamil Nadu; state's tally rises to 50|date=29 March 2020|work=Deccan Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The total number of confirmed cases reached 50.<ref name=\"29Bulletin\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=29 March 2020|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070556/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, 17 new cases were reported, highest till date in the state<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> - 10 male patients from [[Erode]], all of whom have travelled to Delhi were in contact with the Thailand tourists, 5 in Chennai and 1 each in [[Karur]] and [[Madurai]].<ref name=\"30MarchBulletinOld\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_30_03_20_COVID_19_1_11_AM.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_30_03_20_COVID_19_1_11_AM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, 57 new cases were reported, all with a history of travel predominately to [[Delhi]], bringing the total to 124.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-reports-57-new-covid-19-cases-in-one-day-79-attended-tablighi-jamaat-state-tally-at-124-1661904-2020-03-31|title=Tamil Nadu reports 57 new Covid-19 cases in one day, 79% attended Tablighi Jamaat. State tally at 124|date=|work=India Today|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was the highest single day rise till date. 50 of these cases were from [[Namakkal district|Namakkal]] (18), [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli]] (22), [[Kanyakumari district|Kanyakumari]] (4) [[Viluppuram|Villupuram]] (3), [[Madurai district|Madurai]] (2) and [[Thoothukudi district|Thoothukudi]] (1), all had travel history to Delhi.<ref name=\"31MarBulletin2\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070737/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Officials had discovered that at least 80 out of 124 confirmed cases (79 per cent) in Tamil Nadu were from one cluster as they are direct or indirect contact of the two Thai nationals who had tested positive for on 21 March.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /><ref name=\"Hindu-31March\" /> The Thai nationals, identified as patients 5 and 6 were part of a large group from countries including [[Thailand]], [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]], etc. who had visited the state for an annual pilgrimage.<ref name=\"Hindu-31March\">{{Cite news|last=M|first=Serena Josephine|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|title=25 of 67 patients directly or indirectly linked to Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> This group had also attended a 3-day religious congregation event known as ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in [[New Delhi]] in early March.<ref name=\"March31-DH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-25-out-of-67-in-tamil-nadu-have-contact-or-travel-history-with-thai-nationals-819372.html|title=Coronavirus: 25 out of 67 in Tamil Nadu have contact or travel history with Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> It was estimated that more than 1,500 people from the state had participated in this event.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|title=Coimbatore, Erode Stare at Crisis as Tamil Nadu Govt Races to Trace Scores Back from Nizamuddin Event|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Officials also confirmed that the 54-year-old patient who had died the previous week had also participated in the gathering.  Of 1,500 people who were in the gathering, 1,130 had returned to the state. The government had identified and isolated 515 of the 1,130 people.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /> It faced difficulty while trying to map the rest. It had urged people who attended the gathering to step forward and get tested.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Coronavirus update: Tamil Nadu reports 50 more Covid-19 cases {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mar 31|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated:|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Ist|first3=23:31}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\nOn 1 April, the state reported 110 new cases, all attended the Delhi Nizamuddin event. The total became 234.<ref name=\"April1-IT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-new-coronavirus-cases-linked-nizamuddin-event-tabligh-1662243-2020-04-01|title=Tamil Nadu reports 110 new coronavirus cases, all linked to Nizamuddin event|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/110-more-cases-tamil-nadu-wednesday-all-attended-delhi-jamaat-conference-121630|title=110 more cases in Tamil Nadu on Wednesday, all attended Delhi Jamaat conference|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Health Secretary Beela Rajesh said that 1103  out of 1500 attendees of the event had been traced and isolated. 658 of their samples had been tested of which,190 tested positive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-tamil-nadu-witnesses-steep-rise-in-cases/articleshow/74935016.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu witnesses steep rise in cases|date=2020-04-01|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Some of the participants approached officials themselves after government's request.<ref name=\":2\" /> Family members and close contacts were either taken to quarantine facilities or home quarantined.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/special-containment-plan-for-tj-group/articleshow/74939483.cms|title=Tamil Nadu: Special containment plan for Tablighi Jamaat group {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Apr 2|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated:|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=Ist|first3=08:57}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe data below are based on Health and Family Welfare Department of Tamil Nadu daily reports.\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases chart}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases}}\n\n== Testing ==\nAs of 31 March, the state had 17 laboratories (11 government and 6 private) to handle testing for the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_01.04.2020_6_Pages_English_318_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_01.04.2020_6_Pages_English_318_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/List_of_Private_Laboratories_to_test_COVID_19_30_03_2020_3_Pages_English_604_KB.pdf|title=List_of_Private_Laboratories_to_test_COVID_19_30_03_2020_3_Pages_English_604_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070313/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/List_of_Private_Laboratories_to_test_COVID_19_30_03_2020_3_Pages_English_604_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Goverment_COVID_19_Testing_Lab_ICMR_Support_29032020_5_Pages_English_589_KB.pdf|title=Goverment_COVID_19_Testing_Lab_ICMR_Support_29032020_5_Pages_English_589_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070405/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Goverment_COVID_19_Testing_Lab_ICMR_Support_29032020_5_Pages_English_589_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Initially, it had four government labs.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/pulse/956278/why-kerala-has-done-more-coronavirus-tests-than-tamil-nadu-and-why-this-must-change|title=Why Kerala has done more coronavirus tests than Tamil Nadu \u2013 and why this must change|last=Yamunan|first=Sruthisagar|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The government started screening passengers arriving at the airports in January. It had screened 2,10,538 passengers as of 1 April.\n\nDuring the first half of March, the state faced criticism for low number of tests. By 16 March, it had only tested 90 samples while neighboring Kerala and Karnataka had tested more than 1500 and 750 samples.<ref name=\"Testing-TOI\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/in-tamil-nadu-patients-doctors-call-for-increased-tests-on-coronavirus/articleshow/74647117.cms|title=Coronavirus Tamil Nadu Updates: In Tamil Nadu, patients &amp; doctors call for increased tests on coronavirus {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|date=16 March 2020|agency=TNN |website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The director of Public Health defended the state's low number of tests saying that Kerala saw more travel from coronavirus-affected countries which is why it had detected more cases.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\"> The Public Health department has also said that the state follows test protocols established by the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare|Union Health Ministry]].<ref name=\"scroll-tests\"><ref name=\"Testing-TOI\" />\n\nIn order to test community transmission, as of 16 March, the state had tested 22 random samples of people with influenza and severe acute respiratory infection for coronavirus as per [[Indian Council of Medical Research|ICMR]] guidelines. All tested negative.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\">\n\nBy 31 March, as part of the door-to-door surveillance, the government had surveyed 3,96,147 people in 1,08,677 houses in the containment and buffer zones of 12 affected districts for fever and other symptoms. It was carried out by over 2,000 personnel.<ref name=\"containmentDH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-coronavirus-cases-rises-to-74-nizamuddin-link-to-a-chunk-of-it-surfaces-819633.html|title=Tamil Nadu coronavirus cases rises to 74, Nizamuddin link to a chunk of it surfaces|date=2020-03-31|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\"CM-News18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/politics/over-2-lakh-passengers-screened-43000-in-home-quarantine-tamil-nadu-cm-assures-state-ready-to-battle-covid-19-2559869.html|title='Over 2 Lakh Passengers Screened, 43,000 in Home Quarantine': Tamil Nadu CM Assures State Ready to Battle Covid-19|date=2020-04-01|website=News18|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the Delhi Nizamuddin event, authorities said that families of 1103 identified participants will be tested whether or not they show symptoms.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAs of 1 April 2726 samples have been tested of which, 234 were positive.<ref name=\"TNHFW\" />\n\n== Containment measures ==\nStickers announcing that \"COVID-19/Do not Visit/Home under quarantine,\" were pasted on the doors of houses of foreign returnees to warn the public. Authorities had also marked their arms with home quarantine stamps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/24/tamil-nadu-goes-under-lockdown-home-quarantine-stickers-pasted-on-doors-of-foreign-returnees-2121106.html|title=Tamil Nadu goes under lockdown; home quarantine stickers pasted on doors of foreign returnees|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Government launched a mobile application to allow people under home quarantine to interact healthcare professionals for getting medical advice and counselling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-launches-app-to-provide-advice-to-those-under-home-quarantine-816562.html|title=Coronavirus: Tamil Nadu launches app to provide advice to those under home quarantine|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, government announced plans for creating containment zones to stop the community spread.<ref name=\"containmentNews18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|title=Tamil Nadu Prepares for Stage Two of Coronavirus Outbreak With More Home Quarantines, Surveillance|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> On 31 March, the government had created containment zones of 5&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> radius around the residences of infected across 12 districts. The containment zone is ringed by an additional 2&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> buffer zone.<ref name=\"containmentDH\" /><ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /> Active door-to-door surveillance inside these zones along with passive surveillance outside of it to trace the contacts of the infected has been initiated. People found infected are quarantined.<ref name=\"CM-News18\" />\n\nAs of 31 March, '''74,533''' passengers who had returned from affected countries are being monitored under 28 day home quarantine. 3470 have completed this quarantine. '''79''' are currently in institutional quarantine facilities across the state.<ref name=\"Daily30Mar\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|title=Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070449/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Governmental response ==\nThe [[Government of Tamil Nadu|state government]] was among the first to launch measures against COVID-19.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /> On 30 January, it had put 78 people who arrived from China under quarantine.<ref name=\"TNborder\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/coronavirus-outbreak-tamil-nadu-closes-borders-constitutes-task-force-120032201274_1.html|title=Coronavirus outbreak: Tamil Nadu closes borders, constitutes task force|work=Business Standard India|access-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The state government had announced a {{INRConvert|3280|c|year=2020}} relief package on 24 March. It included financial support of {{INRConvert|1000|year=2020}} to all ration card holders, free rice and other essential commodities in the wake of [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]]. It also provided registered [[Hawker (trade)|street vendors]], autorickshaw drivers, migrant labourers and construction workers in the state with similar provisions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/tn-announces-3280-crore-relief-package/article31156022.ece|title=TN announces \u20b93,280-crore relief package|last=Bureau|first=Our|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> It had also announced extension periods of three months to make loan and tax payments for all citizens, and one month to pay house rent for workers including migrants across the state.<ref name=\"RentsTNM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-govt-announces-one-month-rent-freeze-action-can-be-taken-if-house-owners-disobey-121552|title=TN govt announces one month rent freeze for workers, including migrants|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Loans-BS\">{{Cite news|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/covid-19-tamil-nadu-gives-3-month-extension-for-payment-of-taxes-loans-120033101318_1.html|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu gives 3-month extension for payment of taxes, loans|date=31 March 2020|work=Business Standard India|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEarlier, it had allocated sum of {{INRConvert|60|c}} from disaster relief fund to deal with the crisis. It had also taken steps to provide medicines for the next two months to patients with hypertension, diabetes mellitus, HIV and TB while also monitoring pregnant women who are due within that time.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Palaniswami|first=Edappadi K.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/an-eye-each-on-containment-and-welfare/article31221845.ece|title=Tamil Nadu CM writes on how the State is stopping the pandemic in its tracks|date=2020-04-01|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/pregnant-women-to-be-monitored/article31167753.ece|title=Pregnant women to be monitored|date=2020-03-25|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-02|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nNewly built [[Tamil Nadu Government Multi Super Speciality Hospital|Omandurar Government Multispeciality Hospital]] in Chennai was converted with 500 beds to exclusively treat COVID-19 patients.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kannan|first=Ramya|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu-announces-dedicated-hospital-for-covid-19-patients/article31146741.ece|title=Tamil Nadu announces dedicated hospital for COVID-19 patients|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 27 March, the government issued appointment order to recruit 530 doctors, 1,000 nurses and 1,508 lab technicians with immediate effect due to the situation. Orders for 200 new ambulances in the state have also been placed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/india/tamil-nadu-recruits-530-doctors-1508-lab-technicians-1000-nurses-to-contain-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak-cm-k-palaniswami-2272083.html|title=Tamil Nadu recruits 530 doctors, 1508 lab technicians, 1000 nurses to contain coronavirus COVID-19 outbreak: CM K Palaniswami|date=2020-03-27|website=Zee News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"CM-News18\" />\n\nOn 31 March, it announced that house rent cannot be taken from workers, including migrant workers, for a period of one month.<ref name=\"RentsTNM\" /> It also extended the time to make payments including loans and taxes by three months.<ref name=\"Loans-BS\" />\n\nThe government has established helplines for public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/whomtocontact.html|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Contact Information|website=stopcorona.tn.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> It also released an app for officials to monitor people under home quarantine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tn-tracks-movements-of-home-quarantine-people-through-a-mobile-app-817853.html|title=Coronavirus: TN tracks movements of home quarantine people through a mobile app|date=2020-03-26|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Suspensions and closedowns ===\nOn 15 March, Chief minister [[Edappadi K. Palaniswami|Edappadi K Palaniswami]] ordered closure of primary schools throughout the state while shutting theatres, commercial complexes and malls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-govt-to-release-rs-60-crore-disaster-relief-funds-to-tackle-coronavirus-shuts-primary-schools-1655752-2020-03-15|title=Tamil Nadu govt to release Rs 60 crore disaster relief fund to tackle coronavirus, shuts primary schools|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> He had also ordered to close state borders with [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]] and [[Andhra Pradesh]] on March 20 until March 31 and constituted a task force to closely monitor the preventive measures against the viral outbreak.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/tn-closes-border-roads-movement-of-essentials-allowed/1774787|title=TN closes border roads, movement of essentials allowed|last=|first=|date=|website=Outlook India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, the Class 10 SSLC board exams were postponed to beyond April 14, which were due to begin from March 27.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/covid-19-tamil-nadus-class-10-board-exams-postponed/article31127217.ece|title=COVID-19: Tamil Nadu's Class 10 board exams postponed|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> Students of class 1\u20139 in the state will be promoted automatically considering the closure of schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/class-1-9-students-will-be-promoted-in-tamil-nadu-due-to-closure-of-schools-cm-11585134717305.html|title=Class 1-9 students will be promoted in Tamil Nadu due to closure of schools: CM|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the state government extended '[[Janata Curfew|''Janata curfew'']]' to Monday morning 5 am.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-govt-extends-janata-curfew-till-monday-morning/articleshow/74758800.cms|title=Tamil Nadu govt extends 'Janata curfew' till Monday morning|date=2020-03-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The next day, it announced that prohibitory orders under [[Unlawful assembly|Section 144]] will start from 24 March 6 pm until March 31 which prohibits gatherings of more than 5 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-imposes-section-144-week-no-gatherings-more-5-people-120912|title=TN imposes Section 144 for a week, no gatherings of more than 5 people|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=www.thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] announced a [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|nationwide lockdown]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html|title=India places millions under lockdown to fight coronavirus|author1=Helen Regan |author2=Esha Mitra |author3=Swati Gupta|date=|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the nationwide lockdown, Chennai suspended delivery of cooked food from services like [[Swiggy]] and [[Zomato]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shrivastava|first=Aditi|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/chennai-bans-delivery-of-cooked-food/articleshow/74837380.cms?from=mdr|title=Chennai bans delivery of cooked food|date=2020-03-27|work=The Economic Times|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://entrackr.com/2020/03/swiggy-and-zomato-not-allowed-to-deliver-in-tamil-nadu/|title=Swiggy and Zomato not allowed to deliver in Tamil Nadu|last=Upadhyay|first=Harsh|date=26 March 2020|website=Entrackr|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The services were allowed by the government after imposing some regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-tamil-nadu-allows-swiggy-zomato-other-apps-to-home-deliver-cooked-food/articleshow/74852688.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu allows Swiggy, Zomato, other apps to home deliver cooked food {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Sundaram|first=Ram|date=27 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\u200e{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Tamil Nadu}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India by state or union territory|Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:2020s in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Health in Tamil Nadu]]\n", "name_user": "Shanze1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTesting:ref fixes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Tamil_Nadu"}
{"title_page": "Raaz-e-Ulfat", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Raaz-e-Ulfat\n| language       = [[Urdu]] \n| native_name  = {{lang|ur|\u0631\u0627\u0632 \u0627\u064f\u0644\u0641\u062a}}\n| image = raaz e ulfat.jpg\n| genre      = \n| writer      =  [[Maha Malik]]\n| director    =  [[Siraj-ul-Haq]]\n| starring      =  [[Yumna Zaidi]]<br />[[Shehzad Sheikh]]\n| opentheme      = \n| endtheme        = \n| num_episodes      = \n| runtime = \n| producer = [[Abdullah Kadwani]]<br>Asad Qureshi\n| company     = [[7th Sky Entertainment]]\n| distributor     = [[Geo Entertainment]]\n| network      = [[GEO TV]]\n| first_aired      = \n| last_aired       =  \n| preceded_by = \n}}\n\n'''''Raaz-e-Ulfat''''' (''Eng'':''Secret of Love'') is a [[Pakistani]] family drama [[Pakistani dramas|television series]] premiered on [[Geo Entertainment]] on 31 March 2020. It is written by [[Maha Malik]], produced by [[Abdullah Kadwani]] and [[Asad Qureshi]] under [[7th Sky Entertainment]] and directed by [[Siraj-ul-Haq]], it stars [[Shehzad Sheikh]] and [[Yumna Zaidi]] in the lead roles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/magazine/instep-today/633917-looking-at-a-new-season-of-drama-serials|title=Looking at a new season of drama serials|last=Shabbir|first=Buraq|date=|website=The News International|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/magazine/instep-today/591856-yumna-zaidi-gears-up-for-three-tv-roles-in-2020|title=Yumna Zaidi gears up for three TV roles in 2020|last=Shabbir|first=Buraq|date=|website=The News International|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnewshut.com/yumna-zaidi-and-shahzad-sheikh-to-be-seen-in-upcoming-drama-raaz-e-ulfat/|title=Yumna Zaidi and Shahzad Sheikh To Be Seen In Upcoming Drama \"Raaz E Ulfat\"|last=|first=|date=2020-03-23|website=GlobalNews|language=en-US|url-stat