{"title_page": "Olav Ulland", "text_new": "{{Infobox skier\n| name = Olav Ulland\n| image = Ski jumpers 1030.jpeg\n| caption = <small>Ulland is second from the left, 1949</small>\n| nationality = {{flag|Norway}}<br>{{flag|United States}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1910|11|23}}\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2003|6|7|1910|11|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Kongsberg]], Norway\n| death_place = [[Bellevue, Washington]], US\n}}\n\n'''Olav Ulland''' (23 November 1910 &ndash; 7 June 2003) was a Norwegian-American [[ski jumping|ski jumper]] who competed during the 1930s and 1940s.\n\n==Career==\nHe took 5th place at World Championships 1930 in [[Oslo]]. He coached the Italian ski jumping team at Winter Olympics 1936 in [[Garmisch-Partenkirchen]] and took over American national team year later.\n\nIn 1954, Olav Ulland co-founded a new ski club in Seattle, Kongsberger Ski Club, which still exists. From the beginning, the club operated with both ski jumping and cross country skiing, but since 1974 the club has operated only cross country skiing. The United States Ski Association awarded him the Julius Blegen Award in 1957. He was inducted into the US Ski Hall of Fame in 1981.\n\nThe Pacific Northwest Ski Association Regional Ski Association awards the Olav Ulland Award annually to the athlete of the year in the Nordic branches.\n\nOn 17 March 1935 he became the first man in history who jumped over hundred metres at [[Trampolino Gigante Corno d'Aola]] hill in [[Ponte di Legno]], [[Kingdom of Italy]]; but he glided with his hands at 103.5 metres (340&nbsp;ft) and it wasn't recognized as the world record.<ref>{{cite web|title=International Skiing History Association: Hall of Famer Olav Ulland dead at 92|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110423035905/http://skiinghistory.org/ulland.html|publisher=skiinghistory.org|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Invalid ski jumping world record==\nFirst ever ski jump over 100 metres in history.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left; line-height:16px; width:46%;\"\n!style=\"background-color: #ccc;\" width=\"80\"|Date\n!style=\"background-color: #ccc;\" width=\"182\"|Hill\n!style=\"background-color: #ccc;\" width=\"182\"|Location\n!style=\"background-color: #ccc;\" width=\"42\"|Metres\n!style=\"background-color: #ccc;\" width=\"42\"|Feet\n|-bgcolor=#FAEBD7\n| align=right|17 March 1935 &nbsp;\n| [[Trampolino Gigante Corno d\u2019Aola]] \n| [[Ponte di Legno]], [[Kingdom of Italy]]\n| align=center|103.5\n| align=center|340\n|}\n<small>{{color box|#FAEBD7}} Not recognized! Ground touch at world record distance.</small>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://books.google.no/books?id=f1gEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=%22Olav+Ulland%22&source=bl&ots=nzx3XCeiyb&sig=8DTRxuJiWU_ED4z7gbfgBwH50EQ&hl=no&ei=19NTTtP7Condsgb40fnyDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=26&ved=0CPYBEOgBMBk#v=onepage&q=%22Olav%20Ulland%22&f=false Pioneer ski shops: Seattle's Osborn & Ulland] i Skiing Heritage Journal, juni 2006, s. 29-31 (forh\u00e5ndsvist p\u00e5 [[Google Books]])\n* [https://archive.is/20120526204322/http://www.skispringen-com-forum.com/Forum/showthread.php?t=562 Skispringen.com: Weltrekord Skifliegen - complete list] (foruminnlegg 5. mars 2009, redigert 16. juni 2009, bes\u00f8kt 23. August 2011)\n* Jens Jahn, Egon Theiner: ''Enzyklop\u00e4die des Skispringens''. AGON Sportverlag, Kassel 2004. {{ISBN|3-89784-099-5}}, s. 148\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131109184851/http://www.skiforeningen.no/content/download/9484/47538/file/Rekorder.pdf Skiforeningen: Rekorder i Holmenkollbakken] (ikke oppdatert, bes\u00f8kt 23. August 2011)\n* [http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950311&slug=2109464 The Seattle Times: Home Of Sniagrab Going Out Of Business -- Osborn & Ulland Falls Victim To Big Sporting-Goods Chains] (11. mars 1995, bes\u00f8kt 23. August 2011)\n* [http://www.kongsbergers.org/aboutus.html Kongsberger Ski Club: About the Club] (bes\u00f8kt 23. August 2011)\n* [http://www.pnsa.org/Comp%20Manual/2010-2011/AP1%20Awards%2009-10.pdf Pacific Northwest Ski Association: 2009 \u2013 2010 PNSA annual awards]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ulland, Olav}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Norwegian male ski jumpers]]\n[[Category:American male ski jumpers]]\n\n[[de:Olav Ulland]]\n[[no:Olav Ulland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox skier\n| name = Olav Ulland\n| image = Ski jumpers 1030.jpeg\n| caption = <small>Ulland is second from the left, 1949</small>\n| nationality = {{flag|Norway}}<br>{{flag|United States}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1910|11|23}}\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2003|6|7|1910|11|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Kongsberg]], Norway\n| death_place = [[Bellevue, Washington]], US\n}}\n\n'''Olav Ulland''' (23 November 1910 &ndash; 7 June 2003) was a Norwegian-American [[ski jumping|ski jumper]] who competed during the 1930s and 1940s.\n\n==Career==\nHe took 5th place at World Championships 1930 in [[Oslo]]. He coached the Italian ski jumping team at Winter Olympics 1936 in [[Garmisch-Partenkirchen]] and took over American national team year later. \n\nIn 1954, Olav Ulland co-founded a new ski club in Seattle, Kongsberger Ski Club, which still exists. From the beginning, the club operated with both ski jumping and cross country skiing, but since 1974 the club has operated only cross country skiing. The United States Ski Association awarded him the Julius Blegen Award in 1957. He was inducted into the US Ski Hall of Fame in 1981. \n\nThe Pacific Northwest Ski Association Regional Ski Association awards the Olav Ulland Award annually to the athlete of the year in the Nordic branches.\n\nOn 17 March 1935 he became the first man in history who jumped over hundred metres at [[Trampolino Gigante Corno d'Aola]] hill in [[Ponte di Legno]], [[Kingdom of Italy]]; but he glided with his hands at 103.5 metres (340 ft) and it wasn't recognized as the world record.<ref>{{cite web|title=International Skiing History Association: Hall of Famer Olav Ulland dead at 92|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110423035905/http://skiinghistory.org/ulland.html|publisher=skiinghistory.org|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Invalid ski jumping world record==\nFirst ever ski jump over 100 metres in history.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left; line-height:16px; width:46%;\"\n!style=\"background-color: #ccc;\" width=\"80\"|Date\n!style=\"background-color: #ccc;\" width=\"182\"|Hill\n!style=\"background-color: #ccc;\" width=\"182\"|Location\n!style=\"background-color: #ccc;\" width=\"42\"|Metres\n!style=\"background-color: #ccc;\" width=\"42\"|Feet\n|-bgcolor=#FAEBD7\n| align=right|17 March 1935 &nbsp;\n| [[Trampolino Gigante Corno d\u2019Aola]] \n| [[Ponte di Legno]], [[Kingdom of Italy]]\n| align=center|103.5\n| align=center|340\n|}\n<small>{{color box|#FAEBD7}} Not recognized! Ground touch at world record distance.</small>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://books.google.no/books?id=f1gEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=%22Olav+Ulland%22&source=bl&ots=nzx3XCeiyb&sig=8DTRxuJiWU_ED4z7gbfgBwH50EQ&hl=no&ei=19NTTtP7Condsgb40fnyDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=26&ved=0CPYBEOgBMBk#v=onepage&q=%22Olav%20Ulland%22&f=false Pioneer ski shops: Seattle's Osborn & Ulland] i Skiing Heritage Journal, juni 2006, s. 29-31 (forh\u00e5ndsvist p\u00e5 [[Google Books]])\n* [https://archive.is/20120526204322/http://www.skispringen-com-forum.com/Forum/showthread.php?t=562 Skispringen.com: Weltrekord Skifliegen - complete list] (foruminnlegg 5. mars 2009, redigert 16. juni 2009, bes\u00f8kt 23. august 2011)\n* Jens Jahn, Egon Theiner: ''Enzyklop\u00e4die des Skispringens''. AGON Sportverlag, Kassel 2004. {{ISBN|3-89784-099-5}}, s. 148\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131109184851/http://www.skiforeningen.no/content/download/9484/47538/file/Rekorder.pdf Skiforeningen: Rekorder i Holmenkollbakken] (ikke oppdatert, bes\u00f8kt 23. august 2011)\n* [http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950311&slug=2109464 The Seattle Times: Home Of Sniagrab Going Out Of Business -- Osborn & Ulland Falls Victim To Big Sporting-Goods Chains] (11. mars 1995, bes\u00f8kt 23. august 2011)\n* [http://www.kongsbergers.org/aboutus.html Kongsberger Ski Club: About the Club] (bes\u00f8kt 23. august 2011)\n* [http://www.pnsa.org/Comp%20Manual/2010-2011/AP1%20Awards%2009-10.pdf Pacific Northwest Ski Association: 2009 \u2013 2010 PNSA annual awards]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ulland, Olav}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Norwegian male ski jumpers]]\n[[Category:American male ski jumpers]]\n\n[[de:Olav Ulland]]\n[[no:Olav Ulland]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: august 2011) \u2192 August 2011) (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olav_Ulland"}
